# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-anthos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] A **computer cluster** is a group of autonomous computers that work together so that they can be viewed as a single system.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Unlike grid computers, computer clusters have each node set to perform the same task, controlled and scheduled by software.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The newest manifestation of cluster computing is cloud computing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The components of a cluster are usually connected to each other through fast local area networks, with each node (computer used as a server) running its own instance of an operating system.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In most circumstances, all of the nodes use the same hardware and the same operating system, although in some setups (e.g. using Open Source Cluster Application Resources (OSCAR)), different operating systems can be used on each computer, or different hardware.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Clusters are usually deployed to improve performance and availability over that of a single computer, while typically being much more cost-effective than single computers of comparable speed or availability.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Computer clusters emerged as a result of the convergence of a number of computing trends including the availability of low-cost microprocessors, high-speed networks, and software for high-performance distributed computing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] They have a wide range of applicability and deployment, ranging from small business clusters with a handful of nodes to some of the fastest supercomputers in the world such as IBM's Sequoia.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Prior to the advent of clusters, single-unit fault tolerant mainframes with modular redundancy were employed; but the lower upfront cost of clusters, and increased speed of network fabric has favoured the adoption of clusters.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In contrast to high-reliability mainframes, clusters are cheaper to scale out, but also have increased complexity in error handling, as in clusters error modes are not opaque to running programs.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The desire to get more computing power and better reliability by orchestrating a number of low-cost commercial off-the-shelf computers has given rise to a variety of architectures and configurations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The computer clustering approach usually (but not always) connects a number of readily available computing nodes (e.g. personal computers used as servers) via a fast local area network.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The activities of the computing nodes are orchestrated by "clustering middleware", a software layer that sits atop the nodes and allows the users to treat the cluster as by and large one cohesive computing unit, e.g. via a single system image concept.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Computer clustering relies on a centralized management approach which makes the nodes available as orchestrated shared servers.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] It is distinct from other approaches such as peer-to-peer or grid computing which also use many nodes, but with a far more distributed nature.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] A computer cluster may be a simple two-node system which just connects two personal computers, or may be a very fast supercomputer.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] A basic approach to building a cluster is that of a Beowulf cluster which may be built with a few personal computers to produce a cost-effective alternative to traditional high-performance computing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] An early project that showed the viability of the concept was the 133-node Stone Soupercomputer.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The developers used Linux, the Parallel Virtual Machine toolkit and the Message Passing Interface library to achieve high performance at a relatively low cost.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Although a cluster may consist of just a few personal computers connected by a simple network, the cluster architecture may also be used to achieve very high levels of performance.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The TOP500 organization's semiannual list of the 500 fastest supercomputers often includes many clusters, e.g. the world's fastest machine in 2011 was the K computer which has a distributed memory, cluster architecture.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Greg Pfister has stated that clusters were not invented by any specific vendor but by customers who could not fit all their work on one computer, or needed a backup.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Pfister estimates the date as some time in the 1960s.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The formal engineering basis of cluster computing as a means of doing parallel work of any sort was arguably invented by Gene Amdahl of IBM, who in 1967 published what has come to be regarded as the seminal paper on parallel processing: Amdahl's Law.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The history of early computer clusters is more or less directly tied to the history of early networks, as one of the primary motivations for the development of a network was to link computing resources, creating a de facto computer cluster.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The first production system designed as a cluster was the Burroughs B5700 in the mid-1960s.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This allowed up to four computers, each with either one or two processors, to be tightly coupled to a common disk storage subsystem in order to distribute the workload.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Unlike standard multiprocessor systems, each computer could be restarted without disrupting overall operation.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In the early-to-mid-1970s, the General Electric Mark II adopted a high-reliability cluster technology, in which up to eight processing systems (each with its own copy of the operating system) had access to multiple file systems with file-level locking.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In 1984, AT&T released its B3 series computers including a fault-tolerant clustered computing system of two processors.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Clustering per se did not really take off until Digital Equipment Corporation released their VAXcluster product in 1984 for the VMS operating system which, unlike earlier manufacturers, used the term "cluster" in its marketing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The Tandem NonStop, ARC and VAXcluster products not only supported parallel computing, but also shared file systems and peripheral devices.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The idea was to provide the advantages of parallel processing, while maintaining data reliability and uniqueness.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Another noteworthy commercial cluster was the *IBM S/390 Parallel Sysplex* (circa 1994, primarily for business use).
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Within the same time frame, while computer clusters used parallelism outside the computer on a commodity network, supercomputers began to use them within the same computer.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Following the success of the CDC 6600 in 1964, the Cray 1 was delivered in 1976, and introduced internal parallelism via vector processing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] While early supercomputers excluded clusters and relied on shared memory, in time some of the fastest supercomputers (e.g. the K computer) relied on cluster architectures.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Clusters were used for the majority of the world's automated teller machine transactions, credit cards, emergency 911 calls, stock exchanges, largest data warehouses and more by the 1990s if not earlier.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Computer clusters may be configured for different purposes ranging from general purpose business needs such as web-service support, to computation-intensive scientific calculations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In either case, the cluster may use a high-availability approach.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Note that the attributes described below are not exclusive and a "computer cluster" may also use a high-availability approach, etc.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] "Load-balancing" clusters are configurations in which cluster-nodes share computational workload to provide better overall performance.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] For example, a web server cluster may assign different queries to different nodes, so the overall response time will be optimized.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Computer clusters are used for computation-intensive purposes, rather than handling IO-oriented operations such as web service or databases.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] For instance, a computer cluster might support computational simulations of vehicle crashes or weather.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Very tightly coupled computer clusters are designed for work that may approach "supercomputing".
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] "High-availability clusters" (also known as failover clusters, or HA clusters) improve the availability of the cluster approach.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] They operate by having redundant nodes, which are then used to provide service when system components fail.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] HA cluster implementations attempt to use redundancy of cluster components to eliminate single points of failure.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] There are commercial implementations of High-Availability clusters for many operating systems.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The Linux-HA project is one commonly used free software HA package for the Linux operating system.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Scalability is enhanced by adding systems to a cluster, which is the primary basis of massive parallelism.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Unlike symmetric multi-processor systems, where scalability eventually fades as more processors are added (and thus either becomes more expensive or not scalable enough), whereas, for some applications, scalability can be maintained in a loosely-coupled cluster system.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This scalability may require cluster-aware middleware or database to work well.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Clusters are primarily designed with performance in mind, but installations are based on many other factors.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Fault tolerance (*the ability of a system to continue operating despite a malfunctioning node*) enables scalability, and in high-performance situations, allows for a low frequency of maintenance routines, resource consolidation (e.g., RAID), and centralized management.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Advantages include enabling data recovery in the event of a disaster and providing parallel data processing and high processing capacity.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In terms of scalability, clusters provide this in their ability to add nodes horizontally.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This means that more computers may be added to the cluster, to improve its performance, redundancy and fault tolerance.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This can be an inexpensive solution for a higher performing cluster compared to scaling up a single node in the cluster.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This property of computer clusters can allow for larger computational loads to be executed by a larger number of lower performing computers.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] When adding a new node to a cluster, reliability increases because the entire cluster does not need to be taken down.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] A single node can be taken down for maintenance, while the rest of the cluster takes on the load of that individual node.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] If a large number of computers are clustered together, this lends itself to the use of distributed file systems and RAID, both of which can increase the reliability and speed of a cluster.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] One of the issues in designing a cluster is how tightly coupled the individual nodes may be.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] For instance, a single computer job may require frequent communication among nodes: this implies that the cluster shares a dedicated network, is densely located, and probably has homogeneous nodes.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The other extreme is where a computer job uses one or few nodes, and needs little or no inter-node communication, approaching grid computing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In a Beowulf cluster, the application programs never see the computational nodes (also called slave computers) but only interact with the "Master" which is a specific computer handling the scheduling and management of the slaves.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In a typical implementation the Master has two network interfaces, one that communicates with the private Beowulf network for the slaves, the other for the general purpose network of the organization.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The slave computers typically have their own version of the same operating system, and local memory and disk space.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] However, the private slave network may also have a large and shared file server that stores global persistent data, accessed by the slaves as needed.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] A special purpose 144-node DEGIMA cluster is tuned to running astrophysical N-body simulations using the Multiple-Walk parallel tree code, rather than general purpose scientific computations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Due to the increasing computing power of each generation of game consoles, a novel use has emerged where they are repurposed into High-performance computing (HPC) clusters.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Some examples of game console clusters are Sony PlayStation clusters and Microsoft Xbox clusters.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Another example of consumer game product is the Nvidia Tesla Personal Supercomputer workstation, which uses multiple graphics accelerator processor chips.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Besides game consoles, high-end graphics cards too can be used instead.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The use of graphics cards (or rather their GPU's) to do calculations for grid computing is vastly more economical than using CPU's, despite being less precise.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] However, when using double-precision values, they become as precise to work with as CPU's and are still much less costly (purchase cost).
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Computer clusters have historically run on separate physical computers with the same operating system.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] With the advent of virtualization, the cluster nodes may run on separate physical computers with different operating systems which are painted above with a virtual layer to look similar.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The cluster may also be virtualized on various configurations as maintenance takes place; an example implementation is Xen as the virtualization manager with Linux-HA.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] As the computer clusters were appearing during the 1980s, so were supercomputers.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] One of the elements that distinguished the three classes at that time was that the early supercomputers relied on shared memory.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Clusters do not typically use physically shared memory, while many supercomputer architectures have also abandoned it.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] However, the use of a clustered file system is essential in modern computer clusters.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Examples include the IBM General Parallel File System, Microsoft's Cluster Shared Volumes or the Oracle Cluster File System.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Two widely used approaches for communication between cluster nodes are MPI (Message Passing Interface) and PVM (Parallel Virtual Machine).
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] PVM was developed at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory around 1989 before MPI was available.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] PVM must be directly installed on every cluster node and provides a set of software libraries that paint the node as a "parallel virtual machine".
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] PVM provides a run-time environment for message-passing, task and resource management, and fault notification.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] PVM can be used by user programs written in C, C++, or Fortran, etc.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] MPI emerged in the early 1990s out of discussions among 40 organizations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The initial effort was supported by ARPA and National Science Foundation.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Rather than starting anew, the design of MPI drew on various features available in commercial systems of the time.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The MPI specifications then gave rise to specific implementations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] MPI implementations typically use TCP/IP and socket connections.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] MPI is now a widely available communications model that enables parallel programs to be written in languages such as C, Fortran, Python, etc.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Thus, unlike PVM which provides a concrete implementation, MPI is a specification which has been implemented in systems such as MPICH and Open MPI.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] One of the challenges in the use of a computer cluster is the cost of administrating it which can at times be as high as the cost of administrating N independent machines, if the cluster has N nodes.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In some cases this provides an advantage to shared memory architectures with lower administration costs.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This has also made virtual machines popular, due to the ease of administration.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] When a large multi-user cluster needs to access very large amounts of data, task scheduling becomes a challenge.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] In a heterogeneous CPU-GPU cluster with a complex application environment, the performance of each job depends on the characteristics of the underlying cluster.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Therefore, mapping tasks onto CPU cores and GPU devices provides significant challenges.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This is an area of ongoing research; algorithms that combine and extend MapReduce and Hadoop have been proposed and studied.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] When a node in a cluster fails, strategies such as "fencing" may be employed to keep the rest of the system operational.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Fencing is the process of isolating a node or protecting shared resources when a node appears to be malfunctioning.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] There are two classes of fencing methods; one disables a node itself, and the other disallows access to resources such as shared disks.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The STONITH method stands for "Shoot The Other Node In The Head", meaning that the suspected node is disabled or powered off.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] For instance, *power fencing* uses a power controller to turn off an inoperable node.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The *resources fencing* approach disallows access to resources without powering off the node.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This may include *persistent reservation fencing* via the SCSI3, fibre channel fencing to disable the fibre channel port, or global network block device (GNBD) fencing to disable access to the GNBD server.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] However, "computer clusters" which perform complex computations for a small number of users need to take advantage of the parallel processing capabilities of the cluster and partition "the same computation" among several nodes.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Automatic parallelization of programs remains a technical challenge, but parallel programming models can be used to effectuate a higher degree of parallelism via the simultaneous execution of separate portions of a program on different processors.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Developing and debugging parallel programs on a cluster requires parallel language primitives and suitable tools such as those discussed by the *High Performance Debugging Forum* (HPDF) which resulted in the HPD specifications.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Tools such as TotalView were then developed to debug parallel implementations on computer clusters which use Message Passing Interface (MPI) or Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) for message passing.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The University of California, Berkeley *Network of Workstations* (NOW) system gathers cluster data and stores them in a database, while a system such as PARMON, developed in India, allows visually observing and managing large clusters.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Application checkpointing can be used to restore a given state of the system when a node fails during a long multi-node computation.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] This is essential in large clusters, given that as the number of nodes increases, so does the likelihood of node failure under heavy computational loads.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Checkpointing can restore the system to a stable state so that processing can resume without needing to recompute results.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] The Linux world supports various cluster software; for application clustering, there is distcc, and MPICH.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Linux Virtual Server, Linux-HA – director-based clusters that allow incoming requests for services to be distributed across multiple cluster nodes.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] MOSIX, LinuxPMI, Kerrighed, OpenSSI are full-blown clusters integrated into the kernel that provide for automatic process migration among homogeneous nodes.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] OpenSSI, openMosix and Kerrighed are single-system image implementations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Microsoft Windows Cluster Server software, based on the Windows Server platform, originally released in 1997/98, provides cluster support for high-performance computing including the job scheduler, MSMPI library and management tools.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] gLite is a set of middleware technologies created by the Enabling Grids for E-sciencE (EGEE) project.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] slurm is also used to schedule and manage some of the largest supercomputer clusters (see top500 list).
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] Although most computer clusters are permanent fixtures, attempts at flash mob computing have been made to build short-lived clusters for specific computations.
[src:gcp-anthos/cluster-computing] However, larger-scale volunteer computing systems such as BOINC-based systems have had more followers.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:gcp-anthos/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:gcp-anthos/gitops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:gcp-anthos/hybrid-cloud] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] When effectively implemented, multicloud solutions can enhance architectural resilience, reduce dependence on a single vendor, and improve flexibility by leveraging services from different providers.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] However, multicloud strategies also present challenges, including increased operational complexity, security risks, higher costs, and integration difficulties.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] According to the 2024 State of the Cloud Report by Flexera, multi-cloud adoption has continued to rise in 2024.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] Enterprises increasingly silo applications into specific clouds and select best-fit services.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] Key use cases include data analysis in separate clouds and cross-cloud disaster recovery.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] There are several advantages to using a multicloud approach, including the ability to negotiate better pricing with cloud providers, the ability to quickly switch to another provider if needed, and the ability to avoid vendor lock-in.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] Multicloud can also be a good way to hedge against the risks of obsolescence, as it allows you to rely on multiple vendors and open standards, which can prolong the life of your systems.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] Various issues and challenges also present themselves in a multicloud environment.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] Security and governance is more complicated, and more "moving parts" may create resiliency issues.
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] Multicloud differs from hybrid cloud in that it refers to multiple cloud services from different vendors rather than multiple deployment modes (on-premises hardware, and public and private, cloud hosting).
[src:gcp-anthos/multicloud] However, when considering a broad definition of multi-cloud, hybrid cloud can still be regarded as a special form of multi-cloud.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] In software architecture, a **service mesh** is a dedicated infrastructure layer for facilitating service-to-service communications between services or microservices using a proxy.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] A dedicated communication layer can provide numerous benefits, such as providing observability into communications, providing secure connections, and automating retries and backoff for failed requests.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] A service mesh consists of network proxies paired with each service in an application and a set of task-management processes.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] The proxies are called the data plane and the management processes are called the control plane.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] The data plane intercepts calls between different services and processes them; the control plane is the brain of the mesh that coordinates the behavior of proxies and provides APIs for operations and maintenance personnel to manipulate and observe the entire network.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] The service mesh architecture is implemented by software products such as Istio, Cilium, Linkerd, Consul, AWS App Mesh, Kuma, Traefik Mesh, and Greymatter.io.
[src:gcp-anthos/service-mesh] Many service meshes use the Envoy proxy on the data plane.
